2. Read the CSV File as a dataframe¶

In [4]:
raw_data = pd.read_csv("D:\\My Freelancing Projects\\Water Aid\\Jal Shakti Charitable Foundation - Data Cleaning and Analysis\\Data Playground\\Gram Vikas Household Survey_Wateraid_ 2020-03-04.csv",
                      dtype=col_types,
                      parse_dates=["Submitted On",
                                  "Family head details: Name (Family Member 1) (Time Answered)", 
                                  "Year of construction",
                                  "When was your tap connection disconnected?",
                                  "Don't ask: Are there infants in the house? (Time Answered)"
                                 ])

3. Transform Columns¶

In [5]:
### Capitalize the Name of Districts
raw_data["District"] = raw_data["District"].str.upper()

###Capitalize the Name of Janpad
raw_data["Block"] = raw_data["Block"].str.upper()

###Capitalize the Name of Gram Panchayat
raw_data["Gram Panchayat"] = raw_data["Gram Panchayat"].str.upper()

###Capitalize the Name of Village
raw_data["Village"] = raw_data["Village"].str.upper()
In [6]:
### Create a column to identify duplicate records

raw_data["is_duplicate_record"] = raw_data.duplicated(subset=("District",
             "Block",
             "Gram Panchayat",

from IPython.display import display_html
def display_side_by_side(*args):
    html_str=''
    for df in args:
        html_str+=df.to_html()
    display_html(html_str.replace('table','table style="display:inline"'),raw=True)
In [8]:
def display_bar(df=pd.DataFrame,title=str, size=list):
    ax=df.plot.bar(title=title, figsize=size)
    rects = ax.patches
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height + 1, s=height, ha='center', va='bottom')
In [9]:
def display_donut(df=pd.DataFrame,title=str,width=int, height=int,pct=bool):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(width, height), subplot_kw=dict(aspect="equal"))
    suffix = ""
    if pct:
        data = round(df.value_counts(normalize=True)*100,2)
        suffix = " %"
    else:
        data = df.value_counts()
    data = data.rename_axis('Category').to_frame('Counts')
    label = data.index
    wedges, texts = ax.pie(data['Counts'], wedgeprops=dict(width=0.5), startangle=-40)
    bbox_props = dict(boxstyle="square,pad=0.3", fc="w", ec="k", lw=0.72)
    kw = dict(arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="-"),
          bbox=bbox_props, zorder=0, va="center")
    for i, p in enumerate(wedges):
        ang = (p.theta2 - p.theta1)/2. + p.theta1
        y = np.sin(np.deg2rad(ang))
        x = np.cos(np.deg2rad(ang))
        horizontalalignment = {-1: "right", 1: "left"}[int(np.sign(x))]
        connectionstyle = "angle,angleA=0,angleB={}".format(ang)
        kw["arrowprops"].update({"connectionstyle": connectionstyle})
        ax.annotate(label[i]+": "+str(data['Counts'][i])+suffix, xy=(x, y), xytext=(1.35*np.sign(x), 1.4*y),
                    horizontalalignment=horizontalalignment, **kw)
    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.show()
In [10]:
def highlight_max(s):
    '''
    highlight the maximum in a Series yellow.
    '''
    is_max = s == s.max()
    return ['background-color: red' if v else '' for v in is_max]

### Column Name
col_1='Do you have water supply to your house/TBR ?'

### Create a column to identify whether the household does not receive water
raw_data['% of Households with No Water Supply'] = pd.to_numeric(
    raw_data[col_1].apply(lambda x: 100.00 if (x=="No") else 0))

### Create a Pivot % of such households village wise 
villages_with_no_supply = raw_data.pivot_table(index = ['District','Village'],
                    values = ['% of Households with No Water Supply'],
                    aggfunc = {'% of Households with No Water Supply':np.mean}
                    ).sort_values(by='% of Households with No Water Supply', ascending=False)

### Binning the number of villages into % of households not receiving water
bins = [0, 1, 5, 10, 25, 50, 100]

def decompose_multiselect_answers(col=str,options=pd.Series):
    for i in enumerate(options):
        raw_data[col+"-"+str(i[1])]=np.where(raw_data[col].str.contains(i[1])==True,100,0)
